ter his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":11,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":42,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":67,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":80,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Elizabeth Foxley was born in 1248, in Bramshill, Hampshire, England. She married John de Foxley in 1269, in Bramshill, Hampshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in her hometown, and was buried in Bramshill, Hampshire, England."},"et":{"1248–":"1248–Surnud","1250–1305":"1250–1305","1270–1325":"1270–1325","1248–Female":"1248–Surnud","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1325":"1325","1269":"1269","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Bramshill, Hampshire, England":"Bramshill, Hampshire, England"},"fi":{"1248–":"1248–Kuollut","1250–1305":"1250–1305","1270–1325":"1270–1325","1248–Female":"1248–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1325":"1325","1269":"1269","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Bramshill, Hampshire, England":"Bramshill, Hampshire, England"},"fr":{"1248–":"1248–Décédée","1250–1305":"1250–1305","1270–1325":"1270–1325","1248–Female":"1248–Décédée","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1325":"1325","1269":"1269","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Bramshill, Hampshire, England":"Bramshill, Hampshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Elizabeth Foxley est née en 1248, à Bramshill, Hampshire, Angleterre. Elle a épousé John de Foxley en 1269, à Bramshill, Hampshire, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée dans sa ville natale, et a été enterrée à Bramshill, Hampshire, Angleterre."},"de":{"1248–":"1248–Verstorben","1250–1305":"1250–1305","1270–1325":"1270–1325","1248–Female":"1248–Verstorben","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1325":"1325","1269":"1269","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Bramshill, Hampshire, England":"Bramshill, Hampshire, England","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Elizabeth Foxley wurde 1248 in Bramshill, Hampshire, Engla